#: ../../manual/editors/3dview/transform/transform_control/numeric_input.rst:54
msgid "Rotation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/editors/3dview/transform/transform_control/numeric_input.rst:56
msgid ""
"To specify a value for clockwise rotation, press :kbd:`R`, (:kbd:`0` - "
":kbd:`9`), then :kbd:`Return` to confirm. To specify counter-clockwise "
"rotation press :kbd:`R`, :kbd:`Minus`, (kbd:`0` - :kbd:`9`), then "
":kbd:`Return` to confirm. Note that 270 degrees of clockwise rotation is "
"equivalent to -90 degrees of counter-clockwise rotation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/editors/3dview/transform/transform_control/numeric_input.rst:64
msgid "Scaling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/editors/3dview/transform/transform_control/numeric_input.rst:66
msgid ""
"Objects, faces and edges can be scaled by pressing :kbd:`S`, (:kbd:`0` - "
":kbd:`9`), then :kbd:`Return` to confirm., Scaling transformations can "
"also be constrained to an axis by pressing :kbd:`X`, :kbd:`Y` or :kbd:`Z`"
" after pressing :kbd:`S`. Essentially, scaling with numeric values works "
"in almost identical fashion to translation. The primary difference is "
"that by default, scaling applies equally to all three axes. e.g. pressing"
" :kbd:`S`, :kbd:`0`:kbd:`.`:kbd:`5`, :kbd:`Return` will scale an Object "
"by 0.5 on all three axes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/editors/3dview/transform/transform_control/numeric_input.rst:77
msgid "Numeric input via the Properties shelf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/editors/3dview/transform/transform_control/numeric_input.rst:82
msgid ""
"Transformations can also be entered through the Transform panel on the "
"Properties shelf."
msgstr ""

#: ../../manual/editors/3dview/transform/transform_control/numeric_input.rst:85
msgid ""
"It is also possible to enter numeric values for each transformation using"
" the *Transform* panel found on the Properties shelf :kbd:`N`. The "
"*Transform* panel can also be used to prevent transformations along "
"particular axes by clicking the lock icon."
msgstr ""

